# Project Conventions

## Before writing code
- Always read `docs/PRD.md` when starting a new feature
- Propose a plan before making changes to more than 2 files — list what you'll touch and why
- If a feature touches the database, write/update migrations in `supabase/migrations/` AND RLS policies in the same change

## Stack
- Next.js 14+ App Router, TypeScript strict mode, React Server Components by default
- Client components (`'use client'`) only when needed (forms, interactivity, hooks)
- Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui for UI
- Supabase for auth + DB, accessed via `@supabase/ssr` (NOT the old auth-helpers package)
- Resend for email

## File structure
```
app/                    # routes
  (auth)/login/         # public
  (member)/             # member pages, layout enforces auth
  admin/                # admin pages, layout enforces admin role
  api/                  # route handlers
components/
  ui/                   # shadcn primitives
  member/               # member-specific
  admin/                # admin-specific
lib/
  supabase/             # server + client factories
  email/                # Resend wrappers
  utils.ts
types/
  database.ts           # generated from Supabase
supabase/
  migrations/
  seed.sql
docs/
  PRD.md
```

## Code style
- Functional components only, no classes
- Server Components for data fetching; pass data down as props
- Client Components for interactivity — keep them leaf-level, small
- No `any`. If a type is genuinely unknown, use `unknown` and narrow
- Name boolean props affirmatively (`isOpen`, not `hidden`)
- Error handling: every `async` in a server action or route handler wrapped in try/catch with typed error return

## Never do
- Never disable RLS "just to test"
- Never commit secrets; use `.env.local` and add everything to `.env.example`
- Never use `localStorage` for auth state — Supabase SSR handles cookies
- Never call Supabase admin client (service role) from the browser
- Never trust `role` from the client; always re-check server-side
